{"title_page": "Grote Hutcheson", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=October 2018}}\n\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name          = Grote Hutcheson\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image         = \n| image_upright = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| native_name   = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name    = \n| other_name    = \n| nickname      = \n| birth_date    = <!--{{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{birth date|1862|04|01}} if dead-->\n| birth_place   = Cincinnati, Ohio\n| death_date    = <!--{{death date and age|1948|12|14|1948|12|14}}-->\n| death_place   = Saratoga, Cailfornia\n| placeofburial = [[Arlington National Cemetery]]\n| placeofburial_label = \n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}}-->\n| allegiance    = \n| branch        = \n| branch_label  = <!--\"Branch\" or \"Service\"-->\n| serviceyears  = 1884-1924\n| serviceyears_label = \n| rank          = Major General\n| rank_label    = \n| servicenumber = \n| unit          = \n| commands      = \n| battles       = Sioux Indian Camapaign, Spanish\u2013American War, Puerto Rican Expedition, Boxer Rebellion, Mexican Punitive Expedition, World War 1\n| battles_label = \n| awards        = Silver Star, Army and Navy Distinguished Service Medals\n| memorials     = \n| spouse        = <!--Add spouse if reliably sourced--> Rosalie St. George<ref>Herny Blaine Jr, \"Generals in Khaki\", p. 193</ref>\n| children      = \n| relations     = \n| laterwork     = \n| signature     = \n| signature_size = \n| signature_alt = \n| website       = <!--{{URL|example.com}}-->\n| module        = \n}}\n'''Grote Hutcheson''' (1862-1948) was an officer of the [[United States Army|U.S Army]] from 1884 to 1924. After graduating from [[United States Military Academy|USMA]] in 1884, Hutcheson participated in the [[Great Sioux War of 1876]]. During the [[Spanish\u2013American War]], he was Adjutant General of the [[Puerto Rican Campaign]]. From 1899 to 1990, Hutcheson participated in the [[China Relief Expedition]] in which he received two Silver Star Commendations. From 1901 to 1902, Hutcheson was secretary to the [[Governor-General of the Philippines|Military Governor of the Philippines.]] He was then Judge Advocate of the [[Department of the East]] in Governor's Island, New York. From 1904 to 1908 Hutcheson was on the General Staff, serving in the office of Chief of Staff. From 1908 to 1910 and 1915 to 1916, Hutcheson was on the Mexican border. During [[World War I|World War 1]], Hutcheson formed the Port of Embarkation and Norfolk from 1917 to 1918, in which he was awarded the Army and Navy Distinguished Service Medals. Hutcheson commanded the Fourteenth Infantry Division as Major General. From 1920 to 1923, Hutcheson commanded the New York Genderal Intermediate Depot as Brigadier General and the Eleventh Field Artillery Brigade. Hutcheson retired in 1924 due to disabilities as Major General. He retired in [[Saratoga, California]] and lived there until his death in April 14, 1948. Hutcheson was buried at [[Arlington National Cemetery]].<ref>Herny Blaine Jr. \"Generals in Khaki\", p.193-194</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nGrote Hutcheson was born April 1, 1862 to Ebenezer E. Hutcheson and Therese Turpini. Hutcheson attended USMA and graduated twenty-five of thirty-seven of the Class of 1884.<ref>Herny Blain jr, \"Generals in Khaki\", p. 193</ref> Upon graduation, he was promoted to Second Lieutenant in the U.S Army.<ref name=\"auto\">http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Gazetteer/Places/America/United_States/Army/USMA/Cullums_Register/3045*.html, \"Class of 1884:GROTE HUTCHESON\",penelope.uchicago.edu, Feb. 28, 2016</ref>\n\n== Military career ==\n\n=== Frontier Duty ===\nHutcheson served frontier duty in Oklahoma, serving at [[Fort Niobrara|Fort Niobrara, Nebraska]] from September 1885 to 1890. During this time, he was on leave to serve on the Department of the Platte, Rifle Competition, and Rifle Range. From November 1890 to March 27, 1891, Hutcheson was stationed at [[Fort Robinson|Fort Robinson, Nebraska]] and participated during the Pine Ridge Campaign. On April 27, 1891, Hutcheson transferred to the 9th Cavalry at [[Powder River, Wyoming]]. He was assigned to the staff of Brigadier-General [[John J. Coppinger]] at the Department of Platte in Omaha, Nebraska. In 1895, Hutcheson took part in Bannock Indian campaign.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n=== Spanish\u2013American War ===\n\nHutcheson was assigned to Brigadier-General Theodore Schwan as Captain and Adjutant-General. He was stationed at [[Mobile, Alabama]], [[Miami]], and [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]]. On July 23, 1898, he embarked from Port Tampa on an expedition to [[Puerto Rico]] and landed at [[Ponce, Puerto Rico|Ponce]] on July 31, 1898. Hutcheson participated at the [[Battle of Hormigueros]] and the [[Battle Las Marias]] on August 10 and 13. He was on sick leave on August 30, 1898.<ref name=\"auto\"/> For his role in the Spanish\u2013American War, Hutcheson was awarded the Silver Star <ref>Herny Blaine Jr, \"Generals in Khaki\", 193</ref>\n\n===Boxer Rebellion ===\nOn June 9, 1889, Hutcheson was assigned as Adjutant-General of the Department of the Missouri in Omaha Nebraska. From April 1899 to May 1901, Hutcheson traveled to the Philippines and participated in the [[China Relief Expedition]]. He participated at the battle of Yangstun and Pekin. Hutcheson was a representative of the United State at Pao-thin-fu and secretary of the [[Governor-General of the Philippines|military governor of the Philippines]].<ref name=\"auto\"/> Hutcheson received two Silver Star commendations for his role in the China Relief Expedition.\n\n=== Before World War 1 ===\nUpon returning to the United States, Hutcheson was Judge Advocate of the Department of the East on Governor's Island New York from 1903 to 1904. From 1904 to 1908, he was assigned to the General Staff, serving in the office of the Chief of Staff. In 1905, Hutcheson was on a special mission to observe maneuvers of the French Army.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Herny Blaine Jr, \"Generals in Khaki\", p.193</ref> In 1908, he reported at Manila and Zamboanga and commanded Camp Overton, Mindanao until July 1908. From 1908 to 1910, he was Captain of the 6th Cavalry at Fort Des Moines, Iowa. From 1911 to 1915, Hutcheson stationed at Fort Bliss, Fort Riley, and Fort Slocum.<ref>[http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Gazetteer/Places/America/United_States/Army/USMA/Cullums_Register/3045*.html] \"Class of 1884: Grote Hutcheson\",penelope.uchicago.edu</ref>\n\n=== World War 1 ===\n\nFrom November 9, 1916 to April 21, 1917, Hutcheson commanded the Third Cavalry and Inspector-General of Brownsville. During May 1917, He enlarged Fort Sam Houston and Fort Thomas.<ref>http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Gazetteer/Places/America/United_States/Army/USMA/Cullums_Register/3045*.html, \"Class of 1884: Grote Hutcheson\"penelope.uchicago.edu</ref> From 1917 to 1918, Hutcheson, created the Port of Embarkation and Norfolk, for which he was awarded the Army and Navy Distinguished Service Medals.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n=== Later career ===\n\nHutcheson was promoted to major general on August 8, 1918. He commanded the Fourteenth Infantry Division at Camp Cluster, Michigan and transferred it to Camp Meade, Maryland. In 1920, Hutcheson was promoted to Brigadier General. He commanded the New York General Intermediate Deport from 1921 to 1923.<ref>Herny Blaine, \"Generals in Khaki\", P.193</ref> Hutcheson was assigned at Fort Sill, Oklahoma, commanding the eleventh Field Artillery Brigade from October 1, 1922 to July 20, 1924. Hutcheson retired from service due to disabilities.<ref>http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Gazetteer/Places/America/United_States/Army/USMA/Cullums_Register/3045*.html \"Class of 1884: Grote Hutcheson\"</ref>\n\n== Later life ==\n\nFollowing military service, Hutchesnon lived in Saratoga, California until his death in December 14, 1948. Hutcheson was buried at Arlington National Cemetery.<ref>Herny Blaine Jr, \"Generals in Khaki\", p.194</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nOn January 16, 1900, Grote Hutcheson married Rosalie St, George. Hutcheson was an Episcopalian and member of the Order of the Dragon, VFW, Union League Club, and Army and Navy Club.\n<ref>Herny Blaine Jr. \"Generals in Khaki\", p. 193-194</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n=== Silver Star ===\n\n==== Citation ====\n<blockquote>Grote Hutcheson, United States Army, was cited for gallantry in action during the Puerto Rican Expedition in 1898.<ref>https://valor.militarytimes.com/hero/16592#93667, \"Silver Star\nAwarded For Actions During Spanish\u2013American War\", valormilitarytimes,</ref> </blockquote>\n==== Citation ====\n<blockquote> Grote Hutcheson, United States Army, was cited for gallantry in action during the China Relief Expedition in 1900 - 1901. (Second Citation)<ref>https://valor.militarytimes.com/hero/16592#93667, \"Silver Star Awarded for Actions During Spanish American War\", valormilitarytimes</ref></blockquote>\n\n==== Citation ====\n\n<blockquote> Grote Hutcheson, United States Army, was cited for gallantry in action during the China Relief Expedition in 1900 - 1901. (Third Citation) <ref>https://valor.militarytimes.com/hero/16592#93683, \"Awarded for Actions\nDuring China Relief, valormilitarytimes</ref> </blockquote>\n\n=== Army Distinguished Service Medal ===\n\n==== Citation ====\n<blockquote> The President of the United States of America, authorized by Act of Congress, July 9, 1918, takes pleasure in presenting the Army Distinguished Service Medal to Major General Grote Hutcheson, United States Army, for exceptionally meritorious and distinguished services to the Government of the United States, in a duty of great responsibility during World War I, in the administration of the Port of Embarkation, Newport News, Virginia, in connection with the shipment of troops overseas.<ref>https://valor.militarytimes.com/hero/16592, \"Army Distinguished Service Medal\", valormilitarytimes</ref> </blockquote>\n\n=== Navy Distinguished Service Medal ===\n\n==== Citation ====\n\n<blockquote> The President of the United States of America takes pleasure in presenting the Navy Distinguished Service Medal to Major General Grote Hutcheson, United States Army, for distinguished service in the line of his profession as Commanding General, Port of Embarkation, Newport News, Virginia. By his close co-operation with the Commander, Newport News Division, Cruiser and Transport Force, the work of embarking troops and turnaround of transports were greatly expedited.<ref>https://valor.militarytimes.com/hero/16592#23912, \"Navy Distinguished Service Medal\", valormilitarytimes</ref></blockquote>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography ===\n* {{Cite book|title=Generals in Khaki|last=Davis, jr|first=Blaine|publisher=Pentland and Press|year=1998|isbn=978-1571970886|location=Bur Oak, Circle, Raleigh, North Carloina|id=D507.D281998}}\n\n== For Further Reading ==\n*[http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Gazetteer/Places/America/United_States/Army/USMA/Cullums_Register/3045*.html \"Class of 1884: Grote Hutcheson\"], Updated Feb 26 2016, penelope.uchicago\n\n== External links ==\n*https://valor.militarytimes.com/hero/16592#93683\n*{{Find a Grave|49210007}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hutcheson, Grote}}\n[[Category:United States Army generals of World War I]]\n[[Category:1862 births]]\n[[Category:1948 deaths]]\n[[Category:Great Sioux War of 1876]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of the Spanish\u2013American War]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=October 2018}}\n\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name          = Grote Hutcheson\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image         = \n| image_upright = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| native_name   = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name    = \n| other_name    = \n| nickname      = \n| birth_date    = <!--{{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{birth date|1862|04|01}} if dead-->\n| birth_place   = Cincinnati, Ohio\n| death_date    = <!--{{death date and age|1948|12|14|1948|12|14}}-->\n| death_place   = Saratoga, Cailfornia\n| placeofburial = [[Arlington National Cemetery]]\n| placeofburial_label = \n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}}-->\n| allegiance    = \n| branch        = \n| branch_label  = <!--\"Branch\" or \"Service\"-->\n| serviceyears  = 1884-1924\n| serviceyears_label = \n| rank          = Major General\n| rank_label    = \n| servicenumber = \n| unit          = \n| commands      = \n| battles       = Sioux Indian Camapaign, Spanish\u2013American War, Puerto Rican Expedition, Boxer Rebellion, Mexican Punitive Expedition, World War 1\n| battles_label = \n| awards        = Silver Star, Army and Navy Distinguished Service Medals\n| memorials     = \n| spouse        = <!--Add spouse if reliably sourced--> Rosalie St. George<ref>Herny Blaine Jr, \"Generals in Khaki\", p. 193</ref>\n| children      = \n| relations     = \n| laterwork     = \n| signature     = \n| signature_size = \n| signature_alt = \n| website       = <!--{{URL|example.com}}-->\n| module        = \n}}\n'''Grote Hutcheson''' (1862-1948) was an officer of the [[United States Army|U.S Army]] from 1884 to 1924. After graduating from [[United States Military Academy|USMA]] in 1884, Hutcheson participated in the [[Great Sioux War of 1876]]. During the [[Spanish\u2013American War]], he was Adjutant General of the [[Puerto Rican Campaign]]. From 1899 to 1990, Hutcheson participated in the [[China Relief Expedition]] in which he received two Silver Star Commendations. From 1901 to 1902, Hutcheson was secretary to the [[Governor-General of the Philippines|Military Governor of the Philippines.]] He was then Judge Advocate of the [[Department of the East]] in Governor's Island, New York. From 1904 to 1908 Hutcheson was on the General Staff, serving in the office of Chief of Staff. From 1908 to 1910 and 1915 to 1916, Hutcheson was on the Mexican border. During [[World War I|World War 1]], Hutcheson formed the Port of Embarkation and Norfolk from 1917 to 1918, in which he was awarded the Army and Navy Distinguished Service Medals. Hutcheson commanded the Fourteenth Infantry Division as Major General. From 1920 to 1923, Hutcheson commanded the New York Genderal Intermediate Depot as Brigadier General and the Eleventh Field Artillery Brigade. Hutcheson retired in 1924 due to disabilities as Major General. He retired in [[Saratoga, California]] and lived there until his death in April 14, 1948. Hutcheson was buried at [[Arlington National Cemetery]].<ref>Herny Blaine Jr. \"Generals in Khaki\", p.193-194</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nGrote Hutcheson was born April 1, 1862 to Ebenezer E. Hutcheson and Therese Turpini. Hutcheson attended USMA and graduated twenty-five of thirty-seven of the Class of 1884.<ref>Herny Blain jr, \"Generals in Khaki\", p. 193</ref> Upon graduation, he was promoted to Second Lieutenant in the U.S Army.<ref name=\"auto\">http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Gazetteer/Places/America/United_States/Army/USMA/Cullums_Register/3045*.html, \"Class of 1884:GROTE HUTCHESON\",penelope.uchicago.edu, Feb. 28, 2016</ref>\n\n== Military career ==\n\n=== Frontier Duty ===\nHutcheson served frontier duty in Oklahoma, serving at [[Fort Niobrara|Fort Niobrara, Nebraska]] from September 1885 to 1890. During this time, he was on leave to serve on the Department of the Platte, Rifle Competition, and Rifle Range. From November 1890 to March 27, 1891, Hutcheson was stationed at [[Fort Robinson|Fort Robinson, Nebraska]] and participated during the Pine Ridge Campaign. On April 27, 1891, Hutcheson transferred to the 9th Cavalry at [[Powder River, Wyoming]]. He was assigned to the staff of Brigadier-General [[John J. Coppinger]] at the Department of Platte in Omaha, Nebraska. In 1895, Hutcheson took part in Bannock Indian campaign.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n=== Spanish\u2013American War ===\n\nHutcheson was assigned to Brigadier-General Theodore Schwan as Captain and Adjutant-General. He was stationed at [[Mobile, Alabama]], [[Miami]], and [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]]. On July 23, 1898, he embarked from Port Tampa on an expedition to [[Puerto Rico]] and landed at [[Ponce, Puerto Rico|Ponce]] on July 31, 1898. Hutcheson participated at the [[Battle of Hormigueros]] and the [[Battle Las Marias]] on August 10 and 13. He was on sick leave on August 30, 1898.<ref name=\"auto\"/> For his role in the Spanish\u2013American War, Hutcheson was awarded the Silver Star <ref>Herny Blaine Jr, \"Generals in Khaki\", 193</ref>\n\n===Boxer Rebellion ===\nOn June 9, 1889, Hutcheson was assigned as Adjutant-General of the Department of the Missouri in Omaha Nebraska. From April 1899 to May 1901, Hutcheson traveled to the Philippines and participated in the [[China Relief Expedition]]. He participated at the battle of Yangstun and Pekin. Hutcheson was a representative of the United State at Pao-thin-fu and secretary of the [[Governor-General of the Philippines|military governor of the Philippines]].<ref name=\"auto\"/> Hutcheson received two Silver Star commendations for his role in the China Relief Expedition.\n\n=== Before World War 1 ===\nUpon returning to the United States, Hutcheson was Judge Advocate of the Department of the East on Governor's Island New York from 1903 to 1904. From 1904 to 1908, he was assigned to the General Staff, serving in the office of the Chief of Staff. In 1905, Hutcheson was on a special mission to observe maneuvers of the French Army.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Herny Blaine Jr, \"Generals in Khaki\", p.193</ref> In 1908, he reported at Manila and Zamboanga and commanded Camp Overton, Mindanao until July 1908. From 1908 to 1910, he was Captain of the 6th Cavalry at Fort Des Moines, Iowa. From 1911 to 1915, Hutcheson stationed at Fort Bliss, Fort Riley, and Fort Slocum.<ref>[http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Gazetteer/Places/America/United_States/Army/USMA/Cullums_Register/3045*.html] \"Class of 1884: Grote Hutcheson\",penelope.uchicago.edu</ref>\n\n=== World War 1 ===\n\nFrom November 9, 1916 to April 21, 1917, Hutcheson commanded the Third Cavalry and Inspector-General of Brownsville. During May 1917, He enlarged Fort Sam Houston and Fort Thomas.<ref>http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Gazetteer/Places/America/United_States/Army/USMA/Cullums_Register/3045*.html, \"Class of 1884: Grote Hutcheson\"penelope.uchicago.edu</ref> From 1917 to 1918, Hutcheson, created the Port of Embarkation and Norfolk, for which he was awarded the Army and Navy Distinguished Service Medals.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n=== Later career ===\n\nHutcheson was promoted to major general on August 8, 1918. He commanded the Fourteenth Infantry Division at Camp Cluster, Michigan and transferred it to Camp Meade, Maryland. In 1920, Hutcheson was promoted to Brigadier General. He commanded the New York General Intermediate Deport from 1921 to 1923.<ref>Herny Blaine, \"Generals in Khaki\", P.193</ref> Hutcheson was assigned at Fort Sill, Oklahoma, commanding the eleventh Field Artillery Brigade from October 1, 1922 to July 20, 1924. Hutcheson retired from service due to disabilities.<ref>http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Gazetteer/Places/America/United_States/Army/USMA/Cullums_Register/3045*.html \"Class of 1884: Grote Hutcheson\"</ref>\n\n== Later life ==\n\nFollowing military service, Hutchesnon lived in Saratoga, California until his death in December 14, 1948. Hutcheson was buried at Arlington National Cemetery.<ref>Herny Blaine Jr, \"Generals in Khaki\", p.194</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nOn January 16, 1900, Grote Hutcheson married Rosalie St, George. Hutcheson was an Episcopalian and member of the Order of the Dragon, VFW, Union League Club, and Army and Navy Club.\n<ref>Herny Blaine Jr. \"Generals in Khaki\", p. 193-194</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n=== Silver Star ===\n\n==== Citation ====\n<blockquote>Grote Hutcheson, United States Army, was cited for gallantry in action during the Puerto Rican Expedition in 1898.<ref>https://valor.militarytimes.com/hero/16592#93667, \"Silver Star\nAwarded For Actions During Spanish\u2013American War\", valormilitarytimes,</ref> </blockquote>\n==== Citation ====\n<blockquote> Grote Hutcheson, United States Army, was cited for gallantry in action during the China Relief Expedition in 1900 - 1901. (Second Citation)<ref>https://valor.militarytimes.com/hero/16592#93667, \"Silver Star Awarded for Actions During Spanish American War\", valormilitarytimes</ref></blockquote>\n\n==== Citation ====\n\n<blockquote> Grote Hutcheson, United States Army, was cited for gallantry in action during the China Relief Expedition in 1900 - 1901. (Third Citation) <ref>https://valor.militarytimes.com/hero/16592#93683, \"Awarded for Actions\nDuring China Relief, valormilitarytimes</ref> </blockquote>\n\n=== Army Distinguished Service Medal ===\n\n==== Citation ====\n<blockquote> The President of the United States of America, authorized by Act of Congress, July 9, 1918, takes pleasure in presenting the Army Distinguished Service Medal to Major General Grote Hutcheson, United States Army, for exceptionally meritorious and distinguished services to the Government of the United States, in a duty of great responsibility during World War I, in the administration of the Port of Embarkation, Newport News, Virginia, in connection with the shipment of troops overseas.<ref>https://valor.militarytimes.com/hero/16592, \"Army Distinguished Service Medal\", valormilitarytimes</ref> </blockquote>\n\n=== Navy Distinguished Service Medal ===\n\n==== Citation ====\n\n<blockquote> The President of the United States of America takes pleasure in presenting the Navy Distinguished Service Medal to Major General Grote Hutcheson, United States Army, for distinguished service in the line of his profession as Commanding General, Port of Embarkation, Newport News, Virginia. By his close co-operation with the Commander, Newport News Division, Cruiser and Transport Force, the work of embarking troops and turnaround of transports were greatly expedited.<ref>https://valor.militarytimes.com/hero/16592#23912, \"Navy Distinguished Service Medal\", valormilitarytimes</ref></blockquote>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography ===\n* {{Cite book|title=Generals in Khaki|last=Davis, jr|first=Blaine|publisher=Pentland and Press|year=1998|isbn=978-1571970886|location=Bur Oak, Circle, Raleigh, North Carloina|id=D507.D281998}}\n\n== For Further Reading ==\n*[http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Gazetteer/Places/America/United_States/Army/USMA/Cullums_Register/3045*.html \"Class of 1884: Grote Hutcheson\"], Updated Feb 26 2016, penelope.uchicago\n\n== External links ==\n*https://valor.militarytimes.com/hero/16592#93683\n*{{Find a Grave|49210007}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hutcheson, Grote}}\n[[Category:United States Army generals]]\n[[Category:1862 births]]\n[[Category:1948 deaths]]\n[[Category:Great Sioux War of 1876]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of the Spanish\u2013American War]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of World War I]]\n", "name_user": "Aldis90", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grote_Hutcheson"}
{"title_page": "Paul Gallagher (barrister)", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name             = Paul Gallagher\n| honorific-suffix = [[Senior Counsel|SC]]\n| image            = \n| order            = 29th\n| office           = Attorney General of Ireland\n| taoiseach        = {{Ubl|[[Bertie Ahern]]|[[Brian Cowen]]}}\n| term_start       = 14 June 2007\n| term_end         = 9 March 2011\n| predecessor      = [[Rory Brady]]\n| successor        = [[M\u00e1ire Whelan]]\n| birth_name       =\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1955|3|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Tralee]], [[County Kerry]], Ireland\n| death_date       =\n| death_place      =\n| nationality      = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n| party            = \n| spouse           = Bl\u00e1thna Ruane\n| children         = 3\n| alma_mater       = {{Ubl|[[University College Dublin]]|[[University of Cambridge]]|[[King's Inns]]}}\n| signature        = \n|}}\n'''Paul Gallagher''' [[Senior Counsel|SC]] (born 20 March 1955<ref name=\"AG Profile\" />) is an Irish [[barrister]] who served as the [[Attorney General of Ireland]] from 2007 to 2011. He was Attorney General during a period of significant economic difficulty in the [[Republic of Ireland]], advising on the bank guarantee scheme, the establishment of the [[National Asset Management Agency]] and the Troika programme.\n\n==Early life and education==\nGallagher was born in Tralee in 1955 and grew up in Day Place.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tralee man appointed as Attorney General |url=https://www.radiokerry.ie/tralee-man-appointed-as-attorney-general/ |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=Radio Kerry |date=16 June 2007}}</ref> He received his primary education at CBS Tralee and secondary education at [[Castleknock College]].<ref name=\"AG Profile\">{{cite web |title=Summary Resume Of Attorney General Paul Gallagher SC |url=http://www.attorneygeneral.ie/ago/agcv.html |website=Attorney General |accessdate=25 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090308014800/http://www.attorneygeneral.ie/ago/agcv.html |archivedate=8 March 2009 |url-status=usurped}}</ref>\n\nGallagher obtained a [[Bachelor of Civil Law|BCL]] from [[University College Dublin|UCD]] in 1975 and completed a BL degree in the [[King's Inns]] in 1976. He returned to UCD to receive a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in [[history]] and [[economics]], graduating in 1978. He received an LLM degree from the [[University of Cambridge]] in 1979, where he was a member of [[Trinity Hall, Cambridge]].<ref name=\"AG Profile\" />\n\n== Early career==\nGallagher returned to Ireland to be [[called to the Bar]] in 1979. He was called on the same day as his predecessor as Attorney General, [[Rory Brady]].<ref name=\"IT 2009\" /> He became a [[senior counsel]] in 1991.<ref name=\"AG 2007 IT Profile\">{{cite news |title=Attorney General |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/attorney-general-1.1210471 |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=15 June 2007 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe became a [[Bencher]] of the King's Inns in 2005 and he served as vice-chairman of the Bar Council from 1995 to 1996.<ref name=\"WW Legal\" /><ref name=\"AG Profile\" /> As a barrister, he has maintained a practice with a broad expertise including in public law, [[European Union law]], commercial law and competition law.<ref name=\"WW Legal\" /><ref name=\"IT 2007 Healy\" />\n\nPrior to becoming Attorney General, he had appeared in many significant cases. He represented the state in ''[[Zappone v. Revenue Commissioners]]'' in its opposition to the attempt by [[Katherine Zappone]] and [[Ann Louise Gilligan]] to have the legal status of their [[Same-sex marriage in Canada|Canadian marriage]] recognised for tax purposes.<ref name=\"IT 2009\" /> He represented [[Fitzwilton]] in its challenge to the [[Mahon Tribunal|Mahon tribunal]] and a challenge by [[Carroll's]] of tobacco legislation.<ref name=\"IT 2009\" />\n\nIn the area of defamation law, he appeared for Irish newspapers who were being sued for defamation by Ian Bailey, arising out of [[death of Sophie Toscan du Plantier]].<ref name=\"IT 2007 Healy\" /> He also successfully acted for [[Bertie Ahern]] in an action taken against businessman Denis \"Starry\" O'Brien.<ref>{{cite news |title=How O'Brien's lies were exposed |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/how-obriens-lies-were-exposed-26079903.html |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=Irish Independent |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe represented [[Fyffes]] against [[DCC plc]] in an unsuccessful action [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]] on an allegation of [[insider trading]] which lasted for 87 days.<ref name=\"IT 2007 Healy\" /> He appeared again for Fyffes in an appeal to the [[Supreme Court of Ireland]] in 2007, after his appointment as Attorney General. He continued to act for the company as he said he was under a \"professional obligation\".<ref>{{cite news |title=AG to act for Fyffes in court appeal |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/ag-to-act-for-fyffes-in-court-appeal-1.1210703 |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=16 June 2007 |language=en}}</ref> The court overturned the decision of the High Court, finding that the chairman of DCC plc had held inside information.<ref>{{cite news |title=DCC's Flavin bows to pressure and quits |url=https://www.rte.ie/news/business/2008/0527/103841-dcc/ |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=RT\u00c9 News |date=27 May 2008 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Attorney General ==\nHe was nominated to the post of Attorney General by [[Taoiseach]] [[Bertie Ahern]] on 14 June 2007 and renominated by [[Brian Cowen]] on 6 May 2008.<ref name=\"AG Profile\" /> His appointment was unusual at the time as he had not been politically involved with either of the coalition parties [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] or the [[Green Party (Ireland)|Green Party]].<ref name=\"IT 2007 Healy\" /> His role involved providing legal advice to the [[Government of the 30th D\u00e1il]] and supervising all legislation promoted by the government.<ref name=\"Leaders in Law\">{{cite web |title=Paul Gallagher S.C. |url=https://www.leaders-in-law.com/lawyers/paul-gallagher-s-c/ |website=Leaders in Law |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref> In his capacity, he attended meetings of the cabinet.<ref name=\"Kerryman 2015\">{{cite news |title=Tralee barrister had key role in banking talks |url=https://www.independent.ie/regionals/kerryman/news/tralee-barrister-had-key-role-in-banking-talks-30922961.html |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=The Kerryman |date=20 January 2015}}</ref> He was said to be in the office from 7am until 7pm, taking a 15-minute lunch-break. He was noted as being \"impressive public speaker\".<ref name=\"IT 2009\">{{Cite web|first=Carol |last=Coulter |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/weekend/2009/0627/1224249639981.html |title=Brilliance under fire |publisher=[[The Irish Times]] |date=2009-06-27 |accessdate=2009-07-04}}</ref> \n\nHe supervised the drafting of the [[Blasphemy law in the Republic of Ireland#Defamation Act 2009|Defamation Act 2009]]. The criminal of offence of blasphemy was required by the [[Constitution of Ireland]] and he \"designed to be impossible to prosecute\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Former justice minister who introduced blasphemy law backs repeal of constitutional ban |url=https://www.irishlegal.com/article/former-justice-minister-who-introduced-blasphemy-law-backs-repeal-of-constitutional-ban |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=Irish Legal News |date=26 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref> In 2009 he advised the government that it could not impose a pension levy on the Irish judiciary.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McGee |first1=Harry |title=Judges cannot be forced to take pay cut, says Ahern |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/judges-cannot-be-forced-to-take-pay-cut-says-ahern-1.789629 |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHis time as Attorney General overlapped with the [[Post-2008 Irish banking crisis]] and the [[Post-2008 Irish economic downturn]].<ref name=\"Leaders in Law\" /> In the midst of significant market turmoil,<ref>{{cite web |title=Government Bank Guarantee |url=https://www.rte.ie/archives/2018/0927/998454-government-bank-guarantee/ |website=RT\u00c9 Archives |accessdate=25 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Gallagher was among those present on the morning of 30 September 2008 advising the Irish government on its decision to guarantee the liabilities of Ireland's largest banks. He was the only member of the government to be present, aside from the Taoiseach and [[Minister for Finance (Ireland)|Minister for Finance]] [[Brian Lenihan Jnr|Brian Lenihan]].<ref name=\"Kerryman 2015\" /> He also provided legal advice on the establishment of the [[National Asset Management Agency]].<ref name=\"IT 2009\" />\n\nHe advised the government on legal matters arising out of it seeking emergency funding from the [[European Central Bank|ECB]], the [[Eurogroup]] and the [[International Monetary Fund|IMF]] leading to the [[Economic Adjustment Programme for Ireland]].<ref name=\"Banking Inquiry Transcript\">{{cite web |title=Paul Gallagher \u2013 Former Attorney General {{!}} Report of the Joint Committee of Inquiry into the Banking Crisis |url=https://inquiries.oireachtas.ie/banking/hearings/paul-gallagher-former-attorney-general/ |website=Oireachtas |accessdate=25 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> He told an Oireachtas inquiry into the banking crisis in 2015 that he advised the government that it could legally default on \u20ac14 billion of bonds, but the government at the time said it was not acceptable to the international partners.<ref>{{cite news |title='Irish taxpayers could have been spared \u20ac14bn' |url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/business/irish-taxpayers-could-have-been-spared-euro14bn-343284.html |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=www.irishexaminer.com |date=18 July 2015 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nGallagher attended three successive meetings the [[Bilderberg meeting|Bilderberg Group]] between 2010 and 2012.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Reilly |first1=Gavan |title=What are the Bilderberg Meetings - and what's Michael Noonan doing there? |url=https://www.thejournal.ie/what-are-the-bilderberg-meetings-and-whats-michael-noonan-doing-there-472746-Jun2012/ |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=TheJournal.ie |date=2 June 2012 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Return to practice ==\nGallagher resumed his practice as a barrister in 2011. He has repeatedly appeared in cases taken by [[Irish Bank Resolution Corporation]], the state-owned entity established to succeed [[Anglo Irish Bank]], since concluding his term as Attorney General.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Healy |first1=Tim |last2=McDonald |first2=Dearbhail |title=Quinns claim \u20ac2bn Anglo loans used to manipulate share price |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/quinns-claim-2bn-anglo-loans-used-to-manipulate-share-price-26737993.html |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=Irish Independent |date=31 May 2011 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Donnell |first1=Orla |title=High Court told Quinn Group used as 'personal bank' |url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2019/0319/1037375-quinn-group-anglo/ |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=RT\u00c9 News |date=19 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref> He represented the [[Oireachtas]] in proceedings taken by [[Angela Kerins]] in the High Court and subsequent appeals from as far as the Supreme Court.<ref>{{cite news |title=Govt spent over \u20ac426k on barristers' fees defending Angela Kerins cases |url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/govt-spent-over-426k-on-barristers-fees-defending-angela-kerins-cases-946445.html |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=www.irishexaminer.com |date=27 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref> He has acted for the state in an appeal taken by Graham Dwyer to the Supreme Court, the man convicted of the [[murder of Elaine O'Hara]], regarding the applicability of the [[Data Retention Directive]].<ref>{{cite news |title='Enormous amount' at stake in State's Dwyer phone data appeal |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/courts/enormous-amount-at-stake-in-states-dwyer-phone-data-appeal-38791484.html |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=Irish Independent |date=17 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe has appeared in the [[European Court of Justice]] in significant cases with an Irish dimension. He appeared for [[Facebook]] in a data protection case in 2019 and Ireland in an action taken by the [[European Commission]] in the [[EU illegal State aid case against Apple in Ireland]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Another day in court for EU-US data privacy tensions |url=https://diginomica.com/another-day-court-eu-us-data-privacy-tensions |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=diginomica |date=10 July 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mong\u00e1in |first1=Colm \u00d3 |title=Ireland appeals ECJ state aid ruling against Luxembourg |url=https://www.rte.ie/news/business/2020/0219/1116376-ireland-appeals-ecj-state-aid-ruling-against-luxembourg/ |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=RT\u00c9 News |date=19 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe is an [[adjunct professor]] at UCD and a member of its School of Law's Development Council.<ref name=\"Dev Council\">{{cite web |title=UCD Development Council |url=https://www.ucd.ie/law/about/developmentcouncil/ |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref> He is also a fellow of the [[International Society of Barristers]] and the International Academy of Trial Lawyers.<ref name=\"WW Legal\">{{cite web |title=Paul Gallagher SC |url=https://whoswholegal.com/paul-gallagher-sc |website=whoswholegal |accessdate=25 April 2020 |language=En}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGallagher is married to another barrister, Bl\u00e1thna Ruane with whom he lives in [[Ballsbridge]].<ref name=\"IT 2007 Healy\">{{cite news |last1=Healy |first1=Alison |title=New Cabinet: the ins . . . . . . and outs |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/new-cabinet-the-ins-and-outs-1.1210456 |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=15 June 2007 |language=en}}</ref> They have three sons, all of whom also studied law.<ref>{{cite news |title='Top student' tells of delight |url=https://www.independent.ie/breaking-news/irish-news/top-student-tells-of-delight-30505191.html |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=Irish Independent |date=13 August 2014 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{S-bef|before = [[Rory Brady]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title  = {{nowrap|[[Attorney General of Ireland]]}}\n       |years  = 2007\u20132011}}\n{{S-aft|after  = [[M\u00e1ire Whelan]]}}\n{{end}}\n{{Attorneys General of Ireland}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gallagher, Paul}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Irish lawyers]]\n[[Category:Attorneys General of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:People educated at Castleknock College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's Inns]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity Hall, Cambridge]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name             = Paul Gallagher\n| honorific-suffix = [[Senior Counsel|SC]]\n| image            = \n| order            = 29th\n| office           = Attorney General of Ireland\n| taoiseach        = {{Ubl|[[Bertie Ahern]]|[[Brian Cowen]]}}\n| term_start       = 14 June 2007\n| term_end         = 9 March 2011\n| predecessor      = [[Rory Brady]]\n| successor        = [[M\u00e1ire Whelan]]\n| birth_name       =\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1955|3|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Tralee]], [[County Kerry]], Ireland\n| death_date       =\n| death_place      =\n| nationality      = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n| party            = [[Fianna F\u00e1il]]\n| spouse           = Bl\u00e1thna Ruane {{small|(m. 1987)}}\n| children         = 3\n| alma_mater       = {{Ubl|[[University College Dublin]]|[[University of Cambridge]]|[[King's Inns]]}}\n| signature        = \n|}}\n'''Paul Gallagher''' [[Senior Counsel|SC]] (born 20 March 1955<ref name=\"AG Profile\" />) is an Irish [[barrister]] who served as the [[Attorney General of Ireland]] from 2007 to 2011. He was Attorney General during a period of significant economic difficulty in the [[Republic of Ireland]], advising on the bank guarantee scheme, the establishment of the [[National Asset Management Agency]] and the Troika programme.\n\n==Early life and education==\nGallagher was born in Tralee in 1955 and grew up in Day Place.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tralee man appointed as Attorney General |url=https://www.radiokerry.ie/tralee-man-appointed-as-attorney-general/ |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=Radio Kerry |date=16 June 2007}}</ref> He received his primary education at CBS Tralee and secondary education at [[Castleknock College]].<ref name=\"AG Profile\">{{cite web |title=Summary Resume Of Attorney General Paul Gallagher SC |url=http://www.attorneygeneral.ie/ago/agcv.html |website=Attorney General |accessdate=25 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090308014800/http://www.attorneygeneral.ie/ago/agcv.html |archivedate=8 March 2009 |url-status=usurped}}</ref>\n\nGallagher obtained a [[Bachelor of Civil Law|BCL]] from [[University College Dublin|UCD]] in 1975 and completed a BL degree in the [[King's Inns]] in 1976. He returned to UCD to receive a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in [[history]] and [[economics]], graduating in 1978. He received an LLM degree from the [[University of Cambridge]] in 1979, where he was a member of [[Trinity Hall, Cambridge]].<ref name=\"AG Profile\" />\n\n== Early career==\nGallagher returned to Ireland to be [[called to the Bar]] in 1979. He was called on the same day as his predecessor as Attorney General, [[Rory Brady]].<ref name=\"IT 2009\" /> He became a [[senior counsel]] in 1991.<ref name=\"AG 2007 IT Profile\">{{cite news |title=Attorney General |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/attorney-general-1.1210471 |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=15 June 2007 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe became a [[Bencher]] of the King's Inns in 2005 and he served as vice-chairman of the Bar Council from 1995 to 1996.<ref name=\"WW Legal\" /><ref name=\"AG Profile\" /> As a barrister, he has maintained a practice with a broad expertise including in public law, [[European Union law]], commercial law and competition law.<ref name=\"WW Legal\" /><ref name=\"IT 2007 Healy\" />\n\nPrior to becoming Attorney General, he had appeared in many significant cases. He represented the state in ''[[Zappone v. Revenue Commissioners]]'' in its opposition to the attempt by [[Katherine Zappone]] and [[Ann Louise Gilligan]] to have the legal status of their [[Same-sex marriage in Canada|Canadian marriage]] recognised for tax purposes.<ref name=\"IT 2009\" /> He represented [[Fitzwilton]] in its challenge to the [[Mahon Tribunal|Mahon tribunal]] and a challenge by [[Carroll's]] of tobacco legislation.<ref name=\"IT 2009\" />\n\nIn the area of defamation law, he appeared for Irish newspapers who were being sued for defamation by Ian Bailey, arising out of [[death of Sophie Toscan du Plantier]].<ref name=\"IT 2007 Healy\" /> He also successfully acted for [[Bertie Ahern]] in an action taken against businessman Denis \"Starry\" O'Brien.<ref>{{cite news |title=How O'Brien's lies were exposed |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/how-obriens-lies-were-exposed-26079903.html |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=Irish Independent |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe represented [[Fyffes]] against [[DCC plc]] in an unsuccessful action [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]] on an allegation of [[insider trading]] which lasted for 87 days.<ref name=\"IT 2007 Healy\" /> He appeared again for Fyffes in an appeal to the [[Supreme Court of Ireland]] in 2007, after his appointment as Attorney General. He continued to act for the company as he said he was under a \"professional obligation\".<ref>{{cite news |title=AG to act for Fyffes in court appeal |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/ag-to-act-for-fyffes-in-court-appeal-1.1210703 |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=16 June 2007 |language=en}}</ref> The court overturned the decision of the High Court, finding that the chairman of DCC plc had held inside information.<ref>{{cite news |title=DCC's Flavin bows to pressure and quits |url=https://www.rte.ie/news/business/2008/0527/103841-dcc/ |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=RT\u00c9 News |date=27 May 2008 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Attorney General ==\nHe was nominated to the post of Attorney General by [[Taoiseach]] [[Bertie Ahern]] on 14 June 2007 and renominated by [[Brian Cowen]] on 6 May 2008.<ref name=\"AG Profile\" /> His appointment was unusual at the time as he had not been politically involved with either of the coalition parties [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] or the [[Green Party (Ireland)|Green Party]].<ref name=\"IT 2007 Healy\" /> His role involved providing legal advice to the [[Government of the 30th D\u00e1il]] and supervising all legislation promoted by the government.<ref name=\"Leaders in Law\">{{cite web |title=Paul Gallagher S.C. |url=https://www.leaders-in-law.com/lawyers/paul-gallagher-s-c/ |website=Leaders in Law |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref> In his capacity, he attended meetings of the cabinet.<ref name=\"Kerryman 2015\">{{cite news |title=Tralee barrister had key role in banking talks |url=https://www.independent.ie/regionals/kerryman/news/tralee-barrister-had-key-role-in-banking-talks-30922961.html |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=The Kerryman |date=20 January 2015}}</ref> He was said to be in the office from 7am until 7pm, taking a 15-minute lunch-break. He was noted as being \"impressive public speaker\".<ref name=\"IT 2009\">{{Cite web|first=Carol |last=Coulter |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/weekend/2009/0627/1224249639981.html |title=Brilliance under fire |publisher=[[The Irish Times]] |date=2009-06-27 |accessdate=2009-07-04}}</ref> \n\nHe supervised the drafting of the [[Blasphemy law in the Republic of Ireland#Defamation Act 2009|Defamation Act 2009]]. The criminal of offence of blasphemy was required by the [[Constitution of Ireland]] and he \"designed to be impossible to prosecute\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Former justice minister who introduced blasphemy law backs repeal of constitutional ban |url=https://www.irishlegal.com/article/former-justice-minister-who-introduced-blasphemy-law-backs-repeal-of-constitutional-ban |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=Irish Legal News |date=26 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref> In 2009 he advised the government that it could not impose a pension levy on the Irish judiciary.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McGee |first1=Harry |title=Judges cannot be forced to take pay cut, says Ahern |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/judges-cannot-be-forced-to-take-pay-cut-says-ahern-1.789629 |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHis time as Attorney General overlapped with the [[Post-2008 Irish banking crisis]] and the [[Post-2008 Irish economic downturn]].<ref name=\"Leaders in Law\" /> In the midst of significant market turmoil,<ref>{{cite web |title=Government Bank Guarantee |url=https://www.rte.ie/archives/2018/0927/998454-government-bank-guarantee/ |website=RT\u00c9 Archives |accessdate=25 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Gallagher was among those present on the morning of 30 September 2008 advising the Irish government on its decision to guarantee the liabilities of Ireland's largest banks. He was the only member of the government to be present, aside from the Taoiseach and [[Minister for Finance (Ireland)|Minister for Finance]] [[Brian Lenihan Jnr|Brian Lenihan]].<ref name=\"Kerryman 2015\" /> He also provided legal advice on the establishment of the [[National Asset Management Agency]].<ref name=\"IT 2009\" />\n\nHe advised the government on legal matters arising out of it seeking emergency funding from the [[European Central Bank|ECB]], the [[Eurogroup]] and the [[International Monetary Fund|IMF]] leading to the [[Economic Adjustment Programme for Ireland]].<ref name=\"Banking Inquiry Transcript\">{{cite web |title=Paul Gallagher \u2013 Former Attorney General {{!}} Report of the Joint Committee of Inquiry into the Banking Crisis |url=https://inquiries.oireachtas.ie/banking/hearings/paul-gallagher-former-attorney-general/ |website=Oireachtas |accessdate=25 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> He told an Oireachtas inquiry into the banking crisis in 2015 that he advised the government that it could legally default on \u20ac14 billion of bonds, but the government at the time said it was not acceptable to the international partners.<ref>{{cite news |title='Irish taxpayers could have been spared \u20ac14bn' |url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/business/irish-taxpayers-could-have-been-spared-euro14bn-343284.html |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=www.irishexaminer.com |date=18 July 2015 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nGallagher attended three successive meetings the [[Bilderberg meeting|Bilderberg Group]] between 2010 and 2012.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Reilly |first1=Gavan |title=What are the Bilderberg Meetings - and what's Michael Noonan doing there? |url=https://www.thejournal.ie/what-are-the-bilderberg-meetings-and-whats-michael-noonan-doing-there-472746-Jun2012/ |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=TheJournal.ie |date=2 June 2012 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Return to practice ==\nGallagher resumed his practice as a barrister in 2011. He has repeatedly appeared in cases taken by [[Irish Bank Resolution Corporation]], the state-owned entity established to succeed [[Anglo Irish Bank]], since concluding his term as Attorney General.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Healy |first1=Tim |last2=McDonald |first2=Dearbhail |title=Quinns claim \u20ac2bn Anglo loans used to manipulate share price |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/quinns-claim-2bn-anglo-loans-used-to-manipulate-share-price-26737993.html |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=Irish Independent |date=31 May 2011 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Donnell |first1=Orla |title=High Court told Quinn Group used as 'personal bank' |url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2019/0319/1037375-quinn-group-anglo/ |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=RT\u00c9 News |date=19 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref> He represented the [[Oireachtas]] in proceedings taken by [[Angela Kerins]] in the High Court and subsequent appeals from as far as the Supreme Court.<ref>{{cite news |title=Govt spent over \u20ac426k on barristers' fees defending Angela Kerins cases |url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/govt-spent-over-426k-on-barristers-fees-defending-angela-kerins-cases-946445.html |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=www.irishexaminer.com |date=27 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref> He has acted for the state in an appeal taken by Graham Dwyer to the Supreme Court, the man convicted of the [[murder of Elaine O'Hara]], regarding the applicability of the [[Data Retention Directive]].<ref>{{cite news |title='Enormous amount' at stake in State's Dwyer phone data appeal |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/courts/enormous-amount-at-stake-in-states-dwyer-phone-data-appeal-38791484.html |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=Irish Independent |date=17 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe has appeared in the [[European Court of Justice]] in significant cases with an Irish dimension. He appeared for [[Facebook]] in a data protection case in 2019 and Ireland in an action taken by the [[European Commission]] in the [[EU illegal State aid case against Apple in Ireland]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Another day in court for EU-US data privacy tensions |url=https://diginomica.com/another-day-court-eu-us-data-privacy-tensions |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=diginomica |date=10 July 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mong\u00e1in |first1=Colm \u00d3 |title=Ireland appeals ECJ state aid ruling against Luxembourg |url=https://www.rte.ie/news/business/2020/0219/1116376-ireland-appeals-ecj-state-aid-ruling-against-luxembourg/ |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=RT\u00c9 News |date=19 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe is an [[adjunct professor]] at UCD and a member of its School of Law's Development Council.<ref name=\"Dev Council\">{{cite web |title=UCD Development Council |url=https://www.ucd.ie/law/about/developmentcouncil/ |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref> He is also a fellow of the [[International Society of Barristers]] and the International Academy of Trial Lawyers.<ref name=\"WW Legal\">{{cite web |title=Paul Gallagher SC |url=https://whoswholegal.com/paul-gallagher-sc |website=whoswholegal |accessdate=25 April 2020 |language=En}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGallagher is married to another barrister, Bl\u00e1thna Ruane with whom he lives in [[Ballsbridge]].<ref name=\"IT 2007 Healy\">{{cite news |last1=Healy |first1=Alison |title=New Cabinet: the ins . . . . . . and outs |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/new-cabinet-the-ins-and-outs-1.1210456 |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=15 June 2007 |language=en}}</ref> They have three sons, all of whom also studied law.<ref>{{cite news |title='Top student' tells of delight |url=https://www.independent.ie/breaking-news/irish-news/top-student-tells-of-delight-30505191.html |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=Irish Independent |date=13 August 2014 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{S-bef|before = [[Rory Brady]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title  = {{nowrap|[[Attorney General of Ireland]]}}\n       |years  = 2007\u20132011}}\n{{S-aft|after  = [[M\u00e1ire Whelan]]}}\n{{end}}\n{{Attorneys General of Ireland}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gallagher, Paul}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Irish lawyers]]\n[[Category:Attorneys General of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:People educated at Castleknock College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's Inns]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity Hall, Cambridge]]\n", "name_user": "ZL10", "label": "safe", "comment": "remove unsourced information", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Gallagher_(barrister)"}
